her for nearly half a century. Even more influentially, it is the name of her daughter  Queen Elizabeth II  (  b. 1926 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Elisabeth","meanings":["The spelling of   Elizabeth   used in the Authorized Version of the New Testament, and in most modern European languages. This was the name of the mother of John the Baptist (Luke 1:60). Etymologically, the name means ‘God is my oath’, and is therefore identical with <i>Elisheba</i>, the name of the wife of Aaron according to the genealogy at Exodus 6:23. The final element seems to have been altered by association with Hebrew <i>shabbāth</i> ‘Sabbath’."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705195,"age":34,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":1}],"lifeSummary":"When Elizabeth Manningford was born about 1348, in Devon, England, her father, John Manningford, was 10 and her mother, Joan Chastelyn, was 1. She had at least 1 son with Thomas Affeton. She died from 1366 to 1427, in Devon, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"Abt 1328–From 1366 to 1427":"umbes 1348–1366 kuni 1427","1348–1427":"1348–1427","1350–1410":"1350–1410","1385–1467":"1385–1467","1340–1405":"1340–1405","1348–1405":"1348–1405","From 1366 to 1427":"1366 kuni 1427","1348":"1348","1467":"1467","1410":"1410","1385":"1385","1340":"1340","1350":"1350","1382":"1382","Abt 1328":"umbes 1348","1405":"1405","1427":"1427","Of Affeton, Devonshire, England":"Devon, England","Devonshire, England, United Kingdom":"Devon, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"Abt 1328–From 1366 to 1427":"noin 1348–vuodesta 1366 vuoteen 1427","1348–1427":"1348–1427","1350–1410":"1350–1410","1385–14